&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Amaya Alvez in conversation with Jackie Dugard&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Join us for a discussion with Professor Alvez facilitated by Dr Jackie Dugard (senior lecturer at ISHR, and sister iSERP member)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Amaya Alvez Mar&amp;iacute;n is a Law Professor in the Faculty of Legal and Social Sciences at the University of Concepci&amp;oacute;n in Chile, where she focuses on Constitutional Law and Human Rights. She is also a member of the University of Northeastern Law School&amp;rsquo;s International Socio-Economic Rights Project (iSERP).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Between 2021 and 2022, Professor Alvez (who is of Mapuche heritage) was an elected member of the Constituent Assembly that drafted a new, rights-based, post-Pinochet era constitution for Chile. The proposed constitution was put to a mandatory national plebiscite (referred to as the &amp;lsquo;exit plebiscite&amp;rsquo;) on 4 September 2022. Devastatingly for many involved in the drafting, the proposed constitution was rejected (by a vote of 62% to 38%). However, the process to reform the dictatorship-inherited constitution is ongoing, and many lessons have been learned along the way regarding the obstacles and opportunities entailed in undertaking rights-based constitutional reform.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Sponsored by:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Institute for the Study of Human Rights&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Committee on Global Thought&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Institute for Latin American Studies&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
